Mushroom Classification

Hitaishi Bairapureddy

2024-04-16

Summary of Analysis

  • The analysis explored how well K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) and Naive Bayes algorithms can classify mushrooms.

  • Data Preparation -The mushroom data was first checked for missing values, and a technique called KNN imputation was used to fill in any missing data points.

  • Exploratory Data Analysis -To understand the data better, various visualizations were created, including boxplots, histograms, and frequency tables.

  • Feature Selection- To identify the most important features for classification, the analysis involved looking at anova tables, correlations between features and using a technique called Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Based on PCA biplot, 8 features were selected

  • Predictive analytics -We built a classification model using both KNN and Naive Bayes algorithms. Interestingly, KNN achieved maximum accuracy for all k values tested and naive bayes achieved less accuracy when compared to the K-NN

  • Evaluating the model -To ensure this wasnt due to overfitting, the models were evaluated using cross validation, and it appears the high accuracy is genuine.ROC curves were plotted and K-NN model has more area under curve.

Dealing with Outliers

# Loading necessary library
library(dplyr)

# Defining a function to remove outliers using IQR method
remove_outliers <- function(data, numeric_cols, k = 1.5) {
  outliers <- data %>%
    select(all_of(numeric_cols)) %>%
    sapply(function(x) {
      Q1 <- quantile(x, 0.25)
      Q3 <- quantile(x, 0.75)
      IQR <- Q3 - Q1
      lower_bound <- Q1 - k * IQR
      upper_bound <- Q3 + k * IQR
      x[x < lower_bound | x > upper_bound] <- NA
      return(x)
    })
  
  # Removing rows with outliers
  data <- data[complete.cases(outliers), ]
  
  return(data)
}

# Specifying numerical columns in dataset
numeric_cols <- c("cap.diameter", "stem.height", "stem.width")

# Removing outliers from the dataset

library(caret)

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Creating a training control object specifying cross-validation
train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",        # Cross-validation
  number = 10           # Number of folds
)

# Defining the range of k values to try
k_values <- expand.grid(k = seq(1, 20
                                , by = 2))  # Testing odd k values from 1 to 20


x <- norm_data[, names(norm_data) != "class"]
y <- norm_data$class

# Train the KNN model using caret to find the optimal k without additional scaling
knn_results <- train(
  x, y, 
  method = "knn",
  tuneGrid = k_values,
  trControl = train_control,
  metric = "Accuracy"    # specify accuracy as the performance metric
)

# Performing kNN classification and evaluate
perform_knn <- function(k) {
  knn_pred <- knn(train = train_data, test = test_data, cl = train_labels, k = k)
  conf_mat <- CrossTable(x = test_labels, y = knn_pred, prop.chisq = FALSE)  # confusion matrix
  acc <- sum(diag(conf_mat$t)) / sum(conf_mat$t)  # calculating accuracy
  list(accuracy = acc, confusion_matrix = conf_mat)
}

Performing Cross Validation to Check the Overfitting

# Performing kNN classification with cross-validation
perform_knn_cv <- function(k) {
  set.seed(123)  # for reproducibility
  folds <- createFolds(train_labels, k = 5)  # create 5-fold cross-validation
  acc_scores <- numeric(length(folds))
  
  for (i in seq_along(folds)) {
    train_idx <- unlist(folds[-i])  # index for training data
    test_idx <- unlist(folds[i])  # index for test data
    
    train_data_cv <- train_data[train_idx, ]
    train_labels_cv <- train_labels[train_idx]
    test_data_cv <- train_data[test_idx, ]
    test_labels_cv <- train_labels[test_idx]
    
    knn_pred_cv <- knn(train = train_data_cv, test = test_data_cv, cl = train_labels_cv, k = k)
    conf_mat_cv <- confusionMatrix(knn_pred_cv, test_labels_cv)  # confusion matrix
    acc_scores[i] <- conf_mat_cv$overall['Accuracy']  # store accuracy
  }
  
  mean_accuracy <- mean(acc_scores)
  list(accuracy = mean_accuracy, accuracy_scores = acc_scores)
}
# Trying k =1, 3, 4, 5 with cross-validation
cv_results_k1 <- perform_knn_cv(1)
cv_results_k3 <- perform_knn_cv(3)
cv_results_k4 <- perform_knn_cv(4)
cv_results_k5 <- perform_knn_cv(5)

# Performing cross-validation for Naive Bayes model
perform_nb_cv <- function(data, labels, folds) {
  set.seed(123)  # for reproducibility
  acc_scores <- numeric(length(folds))
  
  for (i in seq_along(folds)) {
    train_idx <- unlist(folds[-i])  # index for training data
    test_idx <- unlist(folds[i])  # index for test data
    
    train_data_cv <- data[train_idx, ]
    train_labels_cv <- labels[train_idx]
    test_data_cv <- data[test_idx, ]
    test_labels_cv <- labels[test_idx]
    
    nb_model_cv <- naiveBayes(train_data_cv, as.factor(train_labels_cv))  # train Naive Bayes model
    nb_pred_cv <- predict(nb_model_cv, test_data_cv)  # make predictions
    
    # Convert predictions and labels to factors
    nb_pred_cv <- as.factor(nb_pred_cv)
    test_labels_cv <- as.factor(test_labels_cv)
    
    # Print lengths of predictions and labels
    cat("Length of predictions for fold", i, ":", length(nb_pred_cv), "\n")
    cat("Length of labels for fold", i, ":", length(test_labels_cv), "\n")
    
    conf_mat_cv <- confusionMatrix(nb_pred_cv, test_labels_cv)  # confusion matrix
    acc_scores[i] <- conf_mat_cv$overall['Accuracy']  # store accuracy
  }
  
  mean_accuracy <- mean(acc_scores)
  list(accuracy = mean_accuracy, accuracy_scores = acc_scores)
}
# Create folds for cross-validation
nb_folds <- createFolds(train_labels, k = 5)

# Function to perform kNN classification and evaluate
perform_knn <- function(k) {
  knn_pred <- knn(train = train_data, test = test_data, cl = train_labels, k = k)
  return(list(predictions = as.factor(knn_pred), true_labels = as.factor(test_labels)))
}

# Function to perform Naive Bayes classification and evaluate
perform_naive_bayes <- function() {
  nb_model <- naiveBayes(train_data, as.factor(train_labels))
  nb_pred <- predict(nb_model, test_data)
  return(list(predictions = nb_pred, true_labels = as.factor(test_labels)))
}

# Compute ROC curve for kNN with k = 3
compute_roc_knn <- function() {
  results <- perform_knn(3)
  roc_obj <- roc(results$true_labels, as.numeric(results$predictions))
  return(list(roc_curve = roc_obj, label = "kNN (k = 3)"))
}
# Compute ROC curve for Naive Bayes
compute_roc_naive_bayes <- function() {
  results <- perform_naive_bayes()
  roc_obj <- roc(results$true_labels, as.numeric(results$predictions))
  return(list(roc_curve = roc_obj, label = "Naive Bayes"))
}
# Plot ROC curves for kNN with k = 3 and Naive Bayes
roc_curve_knn <- compute_roc_knn()
## Setting levels: control = 1, case = 2
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc_curve_nb <- compute_roc_naive_bayes()
## Setting levels: control = 1, case = 2
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Plot ROC curves
plot(roc_curve_knn$roc_curve, col = "green", main = "ROC Curves for kNN (k = 3) and Naive Bayes", lwd = 2, xlab = "False Positive Rate (FPR)", ylab = "True Positive Rate (TPR)")
plot(roc_curve_nb$roc_curve, col = "purple", add = TRUE, lwd = 2)
legend("bottomright", legend = c(roc_curve_knn$label, roc_curve_nb$label), col = c("green", "purple"),lwd=2)

Inference: Both KNN and Naive Bayes classifiers perform strong with their ROC curves closing the top-left corner, showing high true positive rates and low false positive rates on almost all thresholds. KNN seems a bit better than Naive Bayes in some situations, particularly in the initial part of the curve, but their performances get close at higher thresholds.
